        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0437.jpg" n="part3_p045.jpg" xml:id="img_0045" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part3_p045.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_45_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>de ses
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>de votre beauement.
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>dʼaprès
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>elle.
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>LECTURE XXXIV, March 10, 956
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>We haveiuscussed the formal ethics, so to speak—the fundamental problem of
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>ethics and religion. Today I come to a special section of the general exhical realm, namely
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>personal cthics, in contrast to detmunal ethics; or as we also could say: individual in contract to
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_45_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>social others. In both of these realms, the problem "Culture and Religion" has a large amount of
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>implications and demands a large amount of answers. Let me first give you a survey on what
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>individual ethics means by speaking about different concepts of individuality.
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>The word " individualism" is used very much as aontical word against special forms of
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>behavier or special structure of society, in our period of history. This word is valid to a certain
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>extent—one CAN speak of modern individualism—but it is valid only in a limited way, because
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_45_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>it uses the word " individual" in an undiferentiated, unqualified way. The first thing we must do,
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>referring
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>to such a term.
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>when we deal with such a concept as individualism, is to make the qualifications
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/> individualism can mean three different things. Let me call the one the religious concept,
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>the other the rational concept, and the third the Renaissance concept. These three are by no means
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>identical and must be discussion in a special way, and it is quite possible that SOME of these concepts
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>are to be conbined with opposite concepts in different structure.
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>The religious concept is the concept of the infinite value of the individual soul in the
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>face of God. The word "infisite value" is not directly biblical; the biblical phrase would be, perhaps,
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>"object of the divine love." But this is true of every human being; there are no differentiation
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>Monsieur,
               <lb facs="#facs_45_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>Monsieur, que
            </p>
            
